---
import ReportLayout from '@/components/ReportLayout.astro';
import FindingCard from '@/components/FindingCard.astro';
---

<ReportLayout title="Quick Buy Modal — Myprotein Protein PLP">

  <section class="report-intro">
    <h1 class="report-h1">UX Audit: Quick Buy Modal</h1>
    <p class="report-meta">Myprotein Protein PLP &mdash; Audited 5 June 2026</p>
    <p class="report-summary">
      This audit covers the Quick Buy modal triggered from product cards on the Protein Powder &amp;
      Protein Shakes PLP at <code>/c/nutrition/protein/</code>. The modal allows users to select a
      flavour and size variant and add to basket without leaving the listing page. The core mechanics
      work — variant selection, quantity, and the add-to-basket action all function — but a critical
      price display bug means the sticky CTA bar shows a stale price when users switch sizes, and
      users have no way to navigate to the full PDP if they need more information before buying.
      The modal also accumulates information (5 content accordions) that sits awkwardly within a
      quick-buy context and points to an unresolved question about what this modal is for.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="findings-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Findings</h2>

    <!-- HIGH PRIORITY -->

    <FindingCard
      title="Sticky CTA price doesn't update when size is changed"
      viewport="Both"
      priority="high"
      ticketType="engineering"
      ticketable={true}
      findingId="sticky-price-stale"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        When a user selects a different size, the price in the upper section of the modal updates
        correctly — but the price displayed immediately beside the ADD TO BASKET button in the
        sticky footer bar does not. After selecting 435G, the top of the modal correctly shows
        <strong>£14.49</strong> (Was £18.99, Save £4.50), but the sticky CTA bar still reads
        <strong>£23.99</strong> (Was £30.99, Save £7.00) — the price for the previously selected
        870G size. DOM inspection confirms both price elements are simultaneously visible, with
        the <code>price-was</code> and <code>price-save</code> elements in the sticky bar bound
        to stale state.
        <img src="/assets/reports/myprotein-quick-buy-modal-2026-06-05/quick-buy-modal-price-mismatch.png" alt="Modal showing 435G selected in size picker but £23.99 (870G price) displayed in the sticky CTA bar" class="finding-img" />
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        The sticky price is the last thing a user reads before hitting ADD TO BASKET. If it shows
        the wrong amount, users are making a purchase decision based on incorrect information.
        At best this damages trust when they see a different amount in their basket; at worst it
        results in an incorrect charge and a returns claim. This is the highest-severity issue
        in the modal — it sits directly adjacent to the purchase action.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Ensure the sticky footer price is bound to the same reactive state as the header price.
        Both elements should update from the same data source when a size variant is selected.
        Treat the sticky bar as a mirror of the header price block, not an independent element.
        Add a regression test that verifies the sticky price matches the header price after every
        size change.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <FindingCard
      title="No link to the full product page"
      viewport="Both"
      priority="high"
      ticketType="engineering"
      ticketable={true}
      findingId="no-pdp-link"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        The modal contains zero links to the full product detail page. DOM inspection confirms
        <code>links: []</code> — there is no "View full product", "See more details", or product
        name hyperlink anywhere in the modal. The product name heading is plain text, not a link.
        Users who want to read reviews, see more product images, check full nutritional info, or
        compare flavour options in detail have no way to get there without dismissing the modal
        and navigating manually.
        <img src="/assets/reports/myprotein-quick-buy-modal-2026-06-05/quick-buy-modal-open.png" alt="Quick Buy modal open showing product name as plain text with no link to PDP" class="finding-img" />
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Quick Buy works for highly confident, repeat purchasers. But many users — especially on a
        protein PLP where flavour and size decisions are considered purchases — will want to
        validate their choice before committing. Without a PDP escape route, their only options
        are to dismiss the modal and lose their place in the grid, or commit blindly. This friction
        will increase modal abandonment and push users away from the quick-buy path entirely.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Make the product name in the modal heading a hyperlink to the PDP. Alternatively, add a
        discrete "View full product →" text link below the product name. The PDP URL is already
        available in the product data (confirmed in DOM: <code>/p/sports-nutrition/impact-whey-protein-milkshake/17755…</code>).
        This is a template change — no design work required.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <FindingCard
      title="Product title overwritten with raw variant data on size/flavour selection"
      viewport="Both"
      priority="high"
      ticketType="engineering"
      ticketable={true}
      findingId="title-variant-pollution"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        When a user selects a size and flavour, the modal heading updates from
        <em>"Impact Whey Protein Milkshake"</em> to
        <em>"Impact Whey Protein Milkshake - 435G - 15servings - Salted Caramel"</em>.
        This is a raw SKU string appended directly to the product name — lowercase "servings",
        no formatting, no separator hierarchy. It reads as a data dump rather than a
        user-facing confirmation of their selection.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        The heading serves as a running confirmation of what's in the basket. A well-formatted
        confirmation ("Impact Whey Protein Milkshake — Salted Caramel, 435g") builds confidence
        at the moment of purchase. A raw SKU string ("Impact Whey Protein Milkshake - 435G -
        15servings - Salted Caramel") signals a technical error and undermines trust. It also
        creates an overly long heading that wraps across two lines, pushing the price and variant
        controls further down.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Keep the product name static in the heading. Display the selected variant as a separate,
        clearly labelled confirmation element below the heading — e.g.
        <code>&lt;p class="selected-variant"&gt;Salted Caramel · 435g · 15 servings&lt;/p&gt;</code>.
        This separates the product identity from the variant selection and formats both legibly.
        Fix the case inconsistency in the size labels (<code>15servings</code> → <code>15 Servings</code>).
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <FindingCard
      title="No ratings or social proof at the point of purchase"
      viewport="Both"
      priority="high"
      ticketType="engineering"
      ticketable={true}
      findingId="modal-no-ratings"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        The modal contains no star rating, review count, or any social proof element. This is
        confirmed by DOM inspection — no <code>[class*="rating"]</code>, <code>[class*="star"]</code>,
        or <code>[class*="review"]</code> elements exist anywhere in the modal. The PLP card that
        triggers the modal shows no ratings either (covered in the separate PLP audit). The user
        reaches the purchase decision point with zero peer validation.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        The add-to-basket action is the highest-value micro-conversion on the site. Ratings are
        one of the most consistently evidenced factors in purchase confidence — particularly for
        nutrition products where efficacy claims require third-party validation. A product like
        Impact Whey Protein with thousands of reviews has significant social proof to show; not
        showing it in the modal is a missed conversion opportunity.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Add the average star rating and review count to the modal, positioned directly below the
        product name. A single line — e.g. ★ 4.7 · 14,203 reviews — is sufficient and takes
        minimal space. Link the review count to the reviews section of the PDP.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <!-- MEDIUM PRIORITY -->

    <FindingCard
      title="Size selector shows no price per option — users can't compare value"
      viewport="Both"
      priority="medium"
      ticketType="design"
      ticketable={true}
      findingId="size-no-price"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        The four size buttons (435G, 870G, 2610G, 4350G) display weight and serving count only.
        No price is shown for each option. To find out what each size costs, users must click each
        button one at a time and read the updated price at the top — four interactions to make a
        value comparison that should be instant.
        <img src="/assets/reports/myprotein-quick-buy-modal-2026-06-05/quick-buy-modal-open.png" alt="Size selector buttons showing weight and servings but no price per option" class="finding-img" />
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Size selection is a considered decision for protein products — price per serving is a
        primary driver. Hiding prices behind individual clicks increases cognitive load at the
        exact moment users are trying to commit. Customers who can't quickly assess value are
        more likely to abandon the modal and go elsewhere or do nothing. The PDP shows a
        per-serving price on size buttons; the modal should match this.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Add the price (and ideally the per-serving cost) to each size button. A two-line format
        works well: <strong>870G · 30 Servings</strong> / <em>£23.99 (80p/serving)</em>. This
        is a design change — a spec is needed before engineering can implement, but the
        underlying price data per SKU is already available in the modal.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <FindingCard
      title="Five content accordions in a quick-buy modal — scope creep"
      viewport="Both"
      priority="medium"
      ticketType="design"
      ticketable={false}
      findingId="modal-accordion-overload"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        Below the ADD TO BASKET button, the modal contains five collapsed accordions: Description,
        Key Benefits, Ingredients, Nutritional Information, and Suggested Use. This is a near-
        complete replica of the PDP information architecture inside a modal overlay.
        <img src="/assets/reports/myprotein-quick-buy-modal-2026-06-05/quick-buy-modal-accordions.png" alt="Modal showing five content accordions below the CTA: Description, Key Benefits, Ingredients, Nutritional Information, Suggested Use" class="finding-img" />
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Quick Buy's job is to reduce friction for users who already know what they want. The
        presence of Ingredients, Nutritional Information, and Suggested Use signals that the modal
        is also trying to serve users who are still researching — a different and conflicting
        intent. A user who opens the Nutritional Information accordion inside a modal overlay is
        having a worse experience than one who reads the same information on the PDP. It also
        pushes the modal's scroll depth significantly, making it feel more like a mini-page than
        a checkout shortcut.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Remove Ingredients, Nutritional Information, and Suggested Use from the modal. These are
        research-phase content that belongs on the PDP. Keep only a short Description and Key
        Benefits (maximum two accordions), and replace the removed sections with a prominent
        "View full product details →" link that directs undecided users to the PDP. Requires a
        design and content decision before implementation.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <FindingCard
      title="Amount selector border-radius is off-token (0px)"
      viewport="Both"
      priority="medium"
      ticketType="engineering"
      ticketable={true}
      findingId="size-btn-border-radius"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        The four size/amount selector buttons have a computed <code>border-radius: 0px</code> —
        completely sharp corners. The design system specifies valid values of 4, 8, 12, 16, 24,
        32, 56, or 9999px; selector chips and option buttons should use <code>8px</code>.
        The selected state is indicated by a full black border (<code>2px solid rgb(0, 0, 0)</code>),
        while unselected buttons use a grey border (<code>2px solid rgb(229, 231, 235)</code>) —
        no other visual differentiation between states.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Sharp corners are inconsistent with the rounded design language used throughout the
        site and create a visually jarring selector within an otherwise rounded modal. The
        selected-state treatment (full black border) is functional but low-contrast against the
        white button background — a stronger selected state (filled background or coloured
        border) would make the active selection more scannable.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Set <code>border-radius: 8px</code> on size selector buttons. Consider strengthening the
        selected state: a teal fill or mint border would be more legible than a plain black border.
        Align with the variant selector pattern used on the PDP if one exists.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <FindingCard
      title="Accessible modal name is generic — 'Quick Buy Modal'"
      viewport="Both"
      priority="medium"
      ticketType="engineering"
      ticketable={true}
      findingId="modal-accessible-name"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        The modal's visually-hidden <code>&lt;h2&gt;</code> — which acts as its accessible name
        for screen readers — reads <em>"Quick Buy Modal"</em>. DOM inspection confirms:
        <code>fontSize: 16px, fontWeight: 400</code>, hidden from visual display. The modal has
        no <code>aria-label</code> or <code>aria-labelledby</code> attribute pointing to the
        product name. A screen reader user opening this modal hears "dialog, Quick Buy Modal"
        with no product context.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        WCAG 4.1.2 (Name, Role, Value) requires interactive components to have meaningful
        accessible names. "Quick Buy Modal" is functionally equivalent to "Dialog" — it tells
        the user nothing about which product they're purchasing. A screen reader user navigating
        multiple modals across the page would have no way to distinguish them. This is a
        meaningful barrier for visually impaired users completing a purchase.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Update the visually-hidden heading to include the product name dynamically:
        e.g. <code>"Quick Buy: Impact Whey Protein Milkshake"</code>. Alternatively, add
        <code>aria-labelledby</code> to the modal element pointing to the visible product name
        heading. Either approach satisfies WCAG 4.1.2 with a single-line template change.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <!-- LOW PRIORITY -->

    <FindingCard
      title="ADD TO BASKET font size is 16px — should be 14px Bold"
      viewport="Both"
      priority="low"
      ticketType="engineering"
      ticketable={true}
      findingId="atb-font-size"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        The ADD TO BASKET button has <code>font-size: 16px</code>. The design system specifies
        button text as <code>14px Bold</code>. The button label is also rendered in uppercase
        (<code>text-transform: uppercase</code> via CSS, matching the PLP QUICK BUY button).
        The design system does not use all-caps on buttons.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Minor token drift, same pattern as the QUICK BUY button on the PLP. Low conversion
        impact but contributes to inconsistency across the site's primary CTAs.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Set <code>font-size: 14px</code> on the ATB button. Remove <code>text-transform:
        uppercase</code> — use "Add to Basket" in title case. These are CSS-only changes to the
        shared button component.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <FindingCard
      title="Close button tap target is 32×32px — below 44px recommendation"
      viewport="Mobile"
      priority="low"
      ticketType="engineering"
      ticketable={true}
      findingId="close-btn-tap-target"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        The ✕ close button is rendered at 32×32px (confirmed via <code>getBoundingClientRect()</code>).
        WCAG 2.5.5 (Target Size) recommends a minimum of 44×44px for interactive touch targets.
        At 32px, the button is dismissable but requires precise tapping on mobile — a meaningful
        friction point for users who want to close the modal quickly.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        A close button that's hard to tap on mobile will cause accidental mis-taps and frustration.
        Given the modal is the primary quick-buy entry point on mobile, the close action must be
        reliably accessible — especially for users who open the modal and then change their mind.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Increase the close button's hit area to at least 44×44px using padding while keeping the
        visual icon at its current size. For example:
        <code>padding: 6px</code> around a 32px icon achieves a 44px target without changing
        the visual design.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <FindingCard
      title="Installment options show logos only — no amounts"
      viewport="Both"
      priority="low"
      ticketType="engineering"
      ticketable={false}
      findingId="installment-no-amounts"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        The modal displays "Installment options available with [PayPal logo] &amp; [Frasers Plus logo]"
        with no indication of what the instalment amounts would be. Users have no way to
        evaluate whether financing makes sense for this product and price without clicking away
        from the modal entirely.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Low impact at current price points (£14–£75), but potentially relevant for larger bundle
        sizes. The instalment display appears to be a global template element rather than
        dynamically calculated — whether showing amounts here is feasible depends on the
        financing integration. At minimum the text should be updated if the amounts can't be
        computed.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        If the instalment amount can be calculated client-side from the selected price, display
        it inline: e.g. "3 payments of £4.83 available with PayPal". If not, consider removing
        the instalment line from the modal — it raises expectations it can't fulfil in context.
        Business decision required before engineering can act.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

  </section>

  <section class="prose-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Design Consistency</h2>
    <p>
      The ADD TO BASKET button correctly carries the brand signature mint ring, implemented as
      <code>border: 2px solid rgb(148, 229, 181)</code> (#94E5B5) — consistent with the design
      system specification. The button uses the correct primary fill (<code>#003942</code>) and
      32px border radius. Font size deviates from spec at 16px (should be 14px) and
      <code>text-transform: uppercase</code> is applied inconsistently with the brand's title-case
      button convention. The size selector buttons have <code>border-radius: 0px</code> — not a
      valid design token; 8px is the correct value for selection chips. The modal's white
      background and shadow treatment appear consistent with other modal patterns on the site.
      Figtree is the computed font family throughout — no fallback fonts detected.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="prose-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Accessibility Notes</h2>
    <p>
      The modal uses <code>role="dialog"</code> and <code>aria-modal="true"</code> correctly.
      However, its accessible name is a generic visually-hidden heading ("Quick Buy Modal")
      with no product context — a WCAG 4.1.2 violation (covered as a dedicated finding above).
      The close button is labelled only by its text content (✕) with no <code>aria-label</code>,
      which is marginally acceptable but "Close" would be more descriptive. Focus management
      was not fully tested but the modal appears to render focusable elements in a logical order
      (close → size buttons → quantity → ATB). The quantity stepper uses plain +/− buttons —
      these should carry <code>aria-label="Increase quantity"</code> / <code>"Decrease quantity"</code>
      to be operable by screen readers. Colour contrast on the ADD TO BASKET button (white on
      dark teal) comfortably exceeds WCAG AA. The "Was" price red background and "Save" green
      background on price badges should be verified for contrast — the text size is small
      (<code>font-size: xs</code>) and the colour combinations may not meet the 4.5:1 AA ratio
      for normal text.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="prose-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Conversion Summary</h2>
    <p>
      The Quick Buy modal has a working add-to-basket flow but is undermined by a critical price
      accuracy bug that directly compromises trust at the moment of purchase. The stale sticky
      price means users switching sizes are shown incorrect information beside the buy button —
      this must be fixed before any other improvement. Beyond the bug, the modal's conversion
      potential is limited by the absence of social proof (no ratings), the absence of a PDP
      escape route for undecided users, and a size selector that forces users to click through
      four options to compare prices. The five content accordions below the CTA are a structural
      issue — the modal is trying to be both a quick-buy shortcut and a mini-PDP simultaneously,
      and does neither well.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="prose-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Recommended Implementation Order</h2>
    <ol class="recommendations">
      <li>Fix sticky CTA price — bind the footer price to the same reactive state as the header price so it updates on size change.</li>
      <li>Add a "View full product →" link — make the product name a hyperlink to the PDP or add a discrete link below the name.</li>
      <li>Add star ratings and review count below the product name.</li>
      <li>Fix product heading — keep the name static; show selected variant as a separate formatted line.</li>
      <li>Add per-option pricing to size selector buttons so users can compare value without clicking each one.</li>
      <li>Remove Ingredients, Nutritional Information, and Suggested Use accordions — replace with "View full product details" link.</li>
      <li>Fix size selector button border-radius to 8px token value.</li>
      <li>Update modal's accessible heading to include product name (WCAG 4.1.2 fix).</li>
      <li>Fix ATB button font-size to 14px and remove text-transform: uppercase.</li>
      <li>Increase close button hit area to 44×44px minimum.</li>
    </ol>
  </section>

</ReportLayout>

<style is:global>
  .finding-card code {
    font-family: Menlo, Monaco, 'Courier New', monospace;
    font-size: 12px;
    background: var(--color-bg-muted);
    padding: 1px 5px;
    border-radius: 4px;
    color: var(--color-text-heading);
  }
</style>

<style>
  .report-intro { margin-bottom: 40px; }
  .report-h1 { font-size: 26px; font-weight: 800; color: var(--color-text-heading); line-height: 1.25; margin-bottom: 6px; }
  .report-meta { font-size: 13px; color: var(--color-text-body); opacity: 0.65; margin-bottom: 14px; }
  .report-summary { font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.7; color: var(--color-text-body); max-width: 680px; }
  .findings-section { margin-bottom: 48px; }
  .section-heading { font-size: 18px; font-weight: 700; color: var(--color-text-heading); margin-bottom: 20px; padding-bottom: 10px; border-bottom: 2px solid rgba(0, 57, 66, 0.1); }
  .prose-section { margin-bottom: 36px; }
  .prose-section p { font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.7; color: var(--color-text-body); }
  .recommendations { padding-left: 20px; display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 10px; }
  .recommendations li { font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.6; color: var(--color-text-body); }
</style>
